ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology and particle size of CDs were characterized by TEM. From Fig. 3
                        a and b it is apparent that the CDs were well dispersed and spherical in shape. The diffraction pattern presented in Fig. 3c indicates the amorphous nature of the synthesized CDs. Furthermore, ImageJ software was used to analyze the size distribution of CDs (Fig. 4
                        ) and it demonstrated that the majority of CDs fall within the range of 3–5 nm with an average size of 3.98 nm. The XRD pattern (Fig. 5
                        ) displays a broad peak at 2θ = 22.47° which corresponds to (002) lattice spacing of carbon based material and also specify the amorphous nature of CDs with the interlayer spacing of 3.95, which is characteristic of carbon with distorted sp2 structure. Surface charge of CDs were established by Zeta potential measurements (Fig. 6
                        ). The zeta potential of CDs in aqueous solution was measured to be −21.9 mV, affirming the high stability of CDs. The negative potential ease the molecule to favourably interact with positively charged species like heavy metal ions.
